    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The reason a minor second interval sounds dissonant is due to its close harmonic relationship. Mathematically, a minor second is a frequency ratio of 9:10 (or approximately 90:100). This ratio is equivalent to about 38 cents (1/288), which is close to the octave, causing the \"意识\" of a third or more distinct pitch. In comparison, a perfect fifth has a frequency ratio of 3:2 (3/2) or 7.142, creating a sense of harmonic stability due to a greater separation from the octave.",
