    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's a start. but you mentioned how it's \"unstable\"—can you go deeper into the physics of that? i've heard something about \"beating\" or frequency interference when the waves are that close together. how does that actually work in the ear?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When two adjacent frequencies, such as C# and C, are close but distinct, the aural system (the ear and brain) perceives a phenomenon called \"beating.\" This occurs due to the interference of the two sound waves, which cause constructive and destructive interference patterns. Constructive interference occurs when the two waves are in phase (i.e., peak-to-peak alignment), creating increased amplitude. Destructive interference happens when the waves are out of phase (peak-to-trough alignment), resulting in a cancellation of amplitude, producing a varying pattern of loud and soft sounds - similar to hearing an oscillating wave.",
      "source": "target",
